&quot;For now, as White, I am avoiding giving Black the opportunity to start a cross-fuseki since I&#039;m trying to get a better grasp of fuseki as a whole.&quot;
That&#039;s fair, though I love the advice that I read... shit! Where did I read it? Well, somewhere I read an author claiming that in his visit to Japan, there was a lot of discussion about narrow vs. wide games. Narrow games had fewer possibilities, more obvious next steps. Wider games had more going on, more paths for development, more complication. And the general agreement was that narrow games favored black, since it offered the clearest way to maintain the advantage of going first. A cross-corner opening is an immediate jump to a wide game, which is why white will usually offer it to black.
White move 10 is another case where as white, I would be delighted to offer a wider game to black by approaching his unfinished corner at R5 rather than approach the top: more groups, more fighting, less territory, and komi becomes a bigger and bigger asset.
